Question

A thief is stealing xots and yivs. Each xot has a mass of 20 kilograms and a volume of 18 liters. Each yiv has a mass of 5 kilograms and a volume of 6 liters. The thief can carry a maximum mass of 100 kilograms and a maximum volume of 108 liters. The profit from each xot is $4.46 and the profit from each yiv is $5.33.

For your convenience, those numbers are organized in the table below.

attribute xot yiv capacity
mass (kg) 20 5 100
volume (L) 18 6 108
profit ($) 4.46 5.33 \(\infty\)

What is the maximum profit the thief can produce? (In dollars.)

Solution

This is an example of linear programming.

Define \(x\) as number of xots and \(y\) as number of yivs. Write the constraints as inequalities.

  • Mass constraint: \(20x+5y \le 100\)
  • Volume constraint: \(18x+6y \le 108\)

We can assume that optimal profit will occur at a boundary, so we can just consider the equations. \[20x+5y = 100\] \[18x+6y = 108\]

If either equation has coefficients that all share a common factor, we can simplify by dividing both sides by the greatest common factor:

\[4x+1y = 20\] \[3x+1y = 18\]

We need to find the \(x\) intercepts and the \(y\) intercepts.

To find the \(x\)-intercepts, set \(y\) to 0.

  • The \(x\)-intercept of the mass constraint: \[4x_{\text{int}1}+(1)(0) = 20 \] \[4x_{\text{int}1} = 20 \] \[x_{\text{int}1} = \frac{20}{4} = 5 \]

  • The \(x\)-intercept of the volume constraint:

\[3x_{\text{int}2}+(1)(0) = 18 \] \[3x_{\text{int}2} = 18 \] \[x_{\text{int}2} = \frac{18}{3} = 6 \]

To find the \(y\)-intercepts, set \(x\) to 0.

  • The \(y\)-intercept of the mass constraint: \[(4)(0)+(1)(y_{\text{int1}}) = 20 \] \[1y_{\text{int}1} = 20 \] \[y_{\text{int}1} = \frac{20}{1} = 20 \]

  • The \(y\)-intercept of the volume constraint:

\[(3)(0)+(1)y_{\text{int2}} = 18 \] \[1y_{\text{int}2} = 18 \] \[y_{\text{int}2} = \frac{18}{1} = 18 \]

To find the intersection of the constraints, I would recommend elimination. Multiply the equations to have matching coefficients for \(y\) terms.

\[4x + 1y = 20\] \[3x + 1y = 18\] Subtract equations.

\[1x + (0)y = 2\]

Simplify.

\[1x = 2\]

Divide by 1.

\[x = 2\]

Plug \(x = 2\) into the first equation. Solve for \(y\).

\[(4)(2)+1y = 20\] \[8+1y = 20\] \[1y = 12\] \[y = 12\]

So, the intersection occurs at \((2,\,12)\).

You can plot the boundaries and shade the feasible region.


The maximum profit could occur at \((0,18)\) or \((2,12)\) or \((5,0)\).

Find those profits, using \(P(x,y)=4.46x+5.33y\).

\[P(0,18)=(4.46)(0)+(5.33)(18) = 95.94\] \[P(2,12)=(4.46)(2)+(5.33)(12) = 72.88\] \[P(5,0)=(4.46)(5)+(5.33)(0) = 22.3\]

So, the maximum profit is $95.94.

It might help to visualize this in 3D, with xots, yivs, and profit on the 3 axes. Sorry, I was not able to make a 3D plot show up here. But, we can add a third dimension by using a color ramp for profit. You can see that since our profit function is linear in \(x\) and linear in \(y\), the profit grows linearly as either xots or yivs are added. Another useful concept is an isoprofit line, which shows all the possible combinations of xots and yivs that would generate the same profit (see contour lines).
